Let me put it a bit better. I do self insert myself into all of the (you)s in a story. I imagine myself as the anon as I read. But not just because I want to cuddle someone. I step into their shoes less as if they were me, and more as if I was looking very literally through someone else's eyes. When I'm writing I try to give the characters a quirk or two I don't have, or have be separate form me in some way. I don't want to fall into the trap of every anon being a 100% self insert because I think that it could hurt stories. I let characters do things I very much wouldn't, or try to imagine what the anon in a situation would do as opposed to me.

I really feel that if you 100% self insert then you hold a character back a bit. I want to be writing characters that make decisions mistakes and choices I simply would never make. Not every time, mind you, but when I can I want to set up an anon as their own unique character in a way. Someone people can identify with on a certain level, or jump into the shoes of at any moment, but who isn't a blank slate.

Take ____ base
Add [Not ____] features, possibly remove some of ____'s distinguishing features
Repeat until desired effect is reached

It could be as simple as adding a shit ton of eyes onto a wolf, or it could be as drastic as adding a ton of features from multiple different animals

Let's take the Xenomorph from the Alien series for example, and list off the inspiration for its design:
>Start with human
>Add armored exoskeleton
>Remove eyes
>Elongate fingers/toes into claws
>vertebrae of a snake, molded with parts of a Rolls Royce for a "biomechanical" feel
>Add secondary pharyngeal jaw

TL;DR: Find a base you want, then just add or remove shit to make it feel "off"
